## SPARQL Query Guidelines
- **Always include the endpoint URL** as a comment at the start: `#+ endpoint: <endpoint-url>`
- **Use only ONE endpoint** per query
- **Base your query on the provided context** (the schema and examples below) — do not invent classes, properties, or namespaces
- **Use the exact prefixes** and class/property names from the schema documentation

## Knowledge Base
The following 31 documents contain relevant query examples and class schemas to help you construct an accurate response:

A direct constituent's best amount PLUS its uncertainty interval (the included minimum/maximum endpoints of the QuantityInterval). The best value is futuram:hasBestValue; the spread is ceonq:hasMinimalValueIncludedOfInterval / ceonq:hasMaximalValueIncludedOfInterval. Each is a qudt:QuantityValue with its own numericValue + unit. The amount hangs off the PartRelation (hasPartRelation -> refersTo the part, hasQuantity the interval).:

```sparql
#+ endpoint: http://localhost:47040/composition/sparql
PREFIX futuram: <https://www.purl.org/futuram#>
PREFIX ceonq: <http://w3id.org/CEON/ontology/quantity/>
PREFIX qudt: <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/>
PREFIX rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#>
SELECT ?best ?low ?high ?unit WHERE {
  ?whole rdfs:label ?wl . FILTER(LCASE(STR(?wl)) = "<whole-instance-label>")
  ?part  rdfs:label ?pl . FILTER(LCASE(STR(?pl)) = "<part-instance-label>")
  ?whole futuram:hasCompositionStatement ?stmt .
  ?stmt  futuram:hasPartRelation ?pr .
  ?pr    futuram:refersTo ?part ;
         futuram:hasQuantity ?qi .
  ?qi futuram:hasBestValue [ qudt:numericValue ?best ; qudt:unit ?unit ] .
  OPTIONAL { ?qi ceonq:hasMinimalValueIncludedOfInterval [ qudt:numericValue ?low ] }
  OPTIONAL { ?qi ceonq:hasMaximalValueIncludedOfInterval [ qudt:numericValue ?high ] }
}
```
The data-quality metadata on a composition part: the DQV quality measurements (Accuracy/Completeness scores via dqv:hasQualityMeasurement -> dqv:isMeasurementOf + dqv:value) carried on the futuram:PartRelation, plus the statement's futuram:hasValidityPeriod (the time scope) and PROV provenance (prov:hadPrimarySource / prov:wasAttributedTo) on the statement. This metadata is one reason the composition model is richer than a flat precomputed view. (There is no per-statement confidence score in this model — quality is the DQV measurements.):

```sparql
#+ endpoint: http://localhost:47040/composition/sparql
PREFIX futuram: <https://www.purl.org/futuram#>
PREFIX dqv: <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#>
PREFIX rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#>
SELECT ?wholeLabel ?partLabel ?metric ?score WHERE {
  ?whole futuram:hasCompositionStatement ?stmt ;
         rdfs:label ?wholeLabel .
  ?stmt  futuram:hasPartRelation ?pr .
  ?pr    futuram:refersTo ?part .
  ?part  rdfs:label ?partLabel .
  OPTIONAL {
    ?pr dqv:hasQualityMeasurement [ dqv:isMeasurementOf ?metric ; dqv:value ?score ] .
  }
} ORDER BY ?wholeLabel ?partLabel
```
The DIRECT (one hop) constituents of a whole and their stated best amounts, with units. Starts from an INSTANCE whose label is known (instances carry labels; classes do not). The whole reaches its statement via futuram:hasCompositionStatement; each part is a futuram:PartRelation (hasPartRelation) whose futuram:refersTo names the constituent and whose futuram:hasQuantity carries the amount. NOTE the unit column: amounts come in more than one qudt:unit — do not compare them without normalising each by its unit's factor. The FILTER literal is a placeholder; substitute the user's term.:

```sparql
#+ endpoint: http://localhost:47040/composition/sparql
PREFIX futuram: <https://www.purl.org/futuram#>
PREFIX ceonq: <http://w3id.org/CEON/ontology/quantity/>
PREFIX qudt: <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/>
PREFIX rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#>
SELECT ?partLabel ?best ?unit WHERE {
  ?whole rdfs:label ?wholeLabel .
  FILTER(LCASE(STR(?wholeLabel)) = "<instance-label>")   # the whole instance's label
  ?whole futuram:hasCompositionStatement ?stmt .
  ?stmt  futuram:hasPartRelation ?pr .
  ?pr    futuram:refersTo ?part ;
         futuram:hasQuantity/futuram:hasBestValue ?bv .
  ?bv qudt:numericValue ?best ; qudt:unit ?unit .
  ?part rdfs:label ?partLabel .
} ORDER BY DESC(?best)
```
Read each stated amount WITH its qudt:unit and NORMALISE to one common base before any math. Do not assume a single unit: amounts come in more than one unit and some are a fixed fraction (e.g. 1/1000) of others. Branch on the ?unit you actually observe and apply that unit's own factor — never hardcode one unit IRI. itemMass is an absolute mass, not a fraction.:

```sparql
#+ endpoint: http://localhost:47040/composition/sparql
PREFIX futuram: <https://www.purl.org/futuram#>
PREFIX qudt: <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/>
PREFIX rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#>
SELECT ?partLabel ?v ?u WHERE {
  ?whole rdfs:label ?wl . FILTER(LCASE(STR(?wl)) = "<instance-label>")
  ?whole futuram:hasCompositionStatement ?stmt .
  ?stmt  futuram:hasPartRelation ?pr .
  ?pr    futuram:refersTo ?part ;
         futuram:hasQuantity/futuram:hasBestValue [ qudt:numericValue ?v ; qudt:unit ?u ] .
  ?part rdfs:label ?partLabel .
  # then in your reasoning: normalised = ?v * factor(?u)   # factor from the unit
} ORDER BY DESC(?v)
```
The amount of a constituent in a whole TWO HOPS down (whole -> middle -> target), computed by MULTIPLYING the two stated fractions after normalising units, then SUMMING parallel paths. This is the manual aggregation the raw composition endpoint forces on you — and it only covers a FIXED two-hop depth. The full answer needs EVERY path from the whole down to the target constituent, recursively, summed, and then meaned over the class's instances — SPARQL 1.1 cannot do unbounded recursive arithmetic in one query, so fix the depth (as here) or pull the statement tree out and aggregate client-side. Each hop is hasCompositionStatement -> hasPartRelation -> refersTo, and the middle part of hop 1 is the whole of hop 2. The literals are placeholders:  the whole,  the target class; convert by each unit's own factor.:

```sparql
#+ endpoint: http://localhost:47040/composition/sparql
PREFIX futuram: <https://www.purl.org/futuram#>
PREFIX qudt: <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/>
PREFIX rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#>
SELECT ?v1 ?u1 ?v2 ?u2 WHERE {
  ?whole rdfs:label ?wl . FILTER(LCASE(STR(?wl)) = "<instance-label>")
  ?whole futuram:hasCompositionStatement ?st1 .
  ?st1   futuram:hasPartRelation ?pr1 .
  ?pr1   futuram:refersTo ?mid ;
         futuram:hasQuantity/futuram:hasBestValue [ qudt:numericValue ?v1 ; qudt:unit ?u1 ] .
  ?mid   futuram:hasCompositionStatement ?st2 .
  ?st2   futuram:hasPartRelation ?pr2 .
  ?pr2   futuram:refersTo ?leaf ;
         futuram:hasQuantity/futuram:hasBestValue [ qudt:numericValue ?v2 ; qudt:unit ?u2 ] .
  ?leaf a <ConstituentIRI> .
  # in your reasoning: f1=?v1*factor(?u1); f2=?v2*factor(?u2); contribution=f1*f2; sum over paths
}
```
The absolute mass of one item, in kilograms, when measured on the instance: futuram:itemMass -> a qudt:QuantityValue (numericValue + unit:KiloGM). Only Product/Component instances carry it. Multiply a kg/kg fraction by this to get absolute kg.:

```sparql
#+ endpoint: http://localhost:47040/composition/sparql
PREFIX futuram: <https://www.purl.org/futuram#>
PREFIX qudt: <http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/>
PREFIX rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#>
SELECT ?label ?kg ?unit WHERE {
  ?inst futuram:itemMass [ qudt:numericValue ?kg ; qudt:unit ?unit ] ;
        rdfs:label ?label .
} ORDER BY DESC(?kg)
```
Which wholes DIRECTLY contain a given constituent class (one hop)? Find instances of the class (substitute ), then the statements whose PartRelation futuram:refersTo one of them, then the whole that hasCompositionStatement that statement. Returns the immediate parents only — not the transitive ancestors.:

```sparql
#+ endpoint: http://localhost:47040/composition/sparql
PREFIX futuram: <https://www.purl.org/futuram#>
PREFIX rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#>
SELECT DISTINCT ?wholeLabel WHERE {
  ?part a <ConstituentIRI> .
  ?pr   futuram:refersTo ?part .
  ?stmt futuram:hasPartRelation ?pr .
  ?whole futuram:hasCompositionStatement ?stmt ;
         rdfs:label ?wholeLabel .
} ORDER BY ?wholeLabel
```
Resolve a class a user NAMES to its INSTANCES — the entry point for any class-level question on this endpoint. CLASSES carry NO rdfs:label here, so match the CLASS IRI LOCAL-NAME (not a label), then reach instances through rdf:type/rdfs:subClassOf* (per-year slices subClassOf the base). These instances are the wholes you traverse from via futuram:hasCompositionStatement. A class-level number is an AGGREGATE over them; this endpoint does not store it. The FILTER literal is a placeholder — substitute the user's term.:

```sparql
#+ endpoint: http://localhost:47040/composition/sparql
PREFIX futuram: <https://www.purl.org/futuram#>
PREFIX rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#>
SELECT DISTINCT ?cls ?inst WHERE {
  ?inst a ?leaf .
  ?leaf rdfs:subClassOf* ?cls .
  FILTER(CONTAINS(LCASE(STR(?cls)), "<term>"))   # match the CLASS IRI local-name
  ?inst futuram:hasCompositionStatement ?stmt .   # keep instances that are wholes
}
```
INSTANCES (not classes) carry rdfs:label here. If you already know an instance's label, find it directly and read its rdf:type to learn its class. Use this only when you have an instance label; to start from a class a user names, use ex:instancesOfClass instead. The FILTER literal is a placeholder.:

```sparql
